The African Dream's Post

The African Dream

February 28  ·
Thomas Sankara was right: "He who feeds you controls you."
Whenever this quote crosses my mind, I feel let down by the ineptitude of our leaders in Africa. Why? Because for far too long—since the days of slavery, through the colonial era, and now in the age of imperialism—Africans have failed to decolonize their minds.
When Thomas Sankara said, "He who feeds you controls you," he wasn’t just talking about food in the literal sense. He was talking about much more. He was referring to our dependence on the IMF, the World Bank, and foreign loans and aid. He was speaking about our reliance on imported grains from the West. He was addressing our dependence on Western nations to process our precious minerals and natural resources. He was highlighting how we look to the West to develop our own countries.
It is disturbing to know that one of the reasons Pan-Africanists call the African Union a "toothless bulldog" is because over 70% of its funding comes from outsiders. Shocking, right? I was shocked too when I learned about this. And worse still, Africa's financial institutions are controlled by the West. Did you know that the United States is the second-largest shareholder of the African Development Bank, after Nigeria? But that’s a discussion for another day.
Let’s talk about the conflicts that have plagued and continue to ravage the continent. The war in the Congo, Boko Haram, the unrest in Mozambique, the insurgency in northern Burkina Faso, the Western-funded Islamist rebel groups in the Sahel. And let’s not forget our past: the assassination of Patrice Lumumba, the murder of Thomas Sankara, the Western-backed killing of Gaddafi—all of these tragedies stem from our dependence on the West. If we were truly independent, both mentally and economically, these atrocities could have been avoided.
"He who feeds you controls you." This dependency led to the betrayal and assassination of our heroes and heroines. Figures like Mobutu Sese Seko and Blaise Compaoré, whose survival depended on the West, turned against their own people.
The Democratic Republic of Congo is bleeding, yet the whole of Africa cannot stop the bleeding. Why? Because almost every African country depends on the West. Their hands are tied, their mouths silenced, because they rely on the very imperialists responsible for Africa’s suffering. How can they resist those who feed them?
The West plotted, invaded, and assassinated Lumumba and Gaddafi right in front of our eyes, yet we couldn’t resist, nor could we stand up to them. Why? Because we are dependent on them.
Africa will only become as powerful as Asia if we decolonize our minds and break free from Western dependence. Look at Asia today—many of its countries have surpassed European nations in development. They boast unimaginable infrastructure, booming agriculture, cutting-edge technology, advancements in medicine, engineering, research, and science. They are not 100% reliant on the West, which is why they can stand toe-to-toe with them. They refuse to be bullied because they never allowed themselves to be fed. Unlike us.
Nigeria has nearly ten times the oil reserves of Dubai. Sierra Leone possesses almost 70% of the world’s minerals. Botswana has the finest diamonds on the planet. The Congo has more minerals than any other country in the world. Ghana produces more gold and cocoa than nearly a third of the world. South Africa has more diamonds, minerals, and natural resources than all of Europe combined.
Yet, despite all these blessings, we remain dependent on the West for almost everything.
East Africa spends billions importing wheat from Ukraine every year. Sierra Leone, with its millions of hectares of arable land, spends hundreds of millions of dollars importing rice annually.
Remember not long ago when President Donald Trump cut funding to USAID? The entire African continent felt the impact—HIV/AIDS programs, malaria prevention initiatives, and crucial medical and health services were shut down. This is the price of dependency.
Did you know that Africa has the highest number of countries indebted to the International Monetary Fund (IMF)? We receive more funding from imperial organizations than any other continent, yet we wonder why they interfere in our affairs. We wonder why they have the audacity to destabilize our nations, assassinate our revolutionaries, and keep our minds colonized.
Despite all the resources God has blessed us with in this Garden of Eden, we still don’t know how to make the most of them.
Indeed, Thomas Sankara was right: "He who feeds you controls you."
